#X text 477 48 Impulse responses should be read into a garray and be linked via symbolic name to the converb~ object. Below is an example method of how to load an IR file., f 58;
#X text 15 8 converb~: A basic convolution reverb external in Pd;
#X text 205 342 <= An example source signal;
#X text 670 160 Info about the IR;
#X text 193 410 Load message for IR file \; note that the symbolic name for the IR array is used., f 29;
#X text 15 147 1 Load in an impulse response file into a garray. See the example to the right for a method of loading in audio files into garrays in Pd., f 60;
#X text 15 199 2 Load the IR into the converb~ object. See below for the proper syntax of the load message., f 60;
#X text 15 234 3 Connect a mono signal to the converb~ inlet and turn on DSP. The mono signal returned from the outlet is convolved with the loaded impulse response \, creating a reverb effect., f 60;
#X text 15 48 converb~ is an external that generates convolution reverb for a given mono source signal. The algorithm for this is efficient enough for real-time use \, and delay time is directly proportional to the length of the impulse response.;
#X text 15 116 The basic usage of this external is given below., f 60;
#X text 476 384 Technical notes:;
#X text 476 405 * This external uses the FFTW library to generate and multiply DFTs. This is the same library used in the rfft~ internal., f 59;
#X text 476 454 * The convolution used in this external is *not* partitioned. That means that the delay is only reliant on the length of the IR \, and cannot be specified by the user. (This could be a possible improvement for future iterations of the external.);
#X text 476 530 * For the DFTs \, the flag FFTW_ESTIMATE was used. This produces DFTs that are less accurate for the sake of improved performance., f 59;
